#   Last push  : 2026-05-19
#
# WHAT IT IS
#   breakpoint adds programmable "breakpoints" to CI workflows.
#   A CI job invokes `breakpoint start` (typically with a config
#   file describing trigger conditions, allowed SSH keys, and
#   notification webhooks), and on the trigger the job pauses,
#   opens an SSH endpoint, and notifies the configured Slack
#   channel(s) so the engineer can `breakpoint attach`, debug
#   the live workflow, then `breakpoint resume` (or `breakpoint
#   extend` the hold).  Useful for catching flaky CI failures —
#   the workflow is paused at the failing step, the engineer
#   gets a Slack notification with the SSH endpoint, jacks in,
#   reproduces and fixes the issue inside the same workflow
#   state, and resumes the job from the breakpoint instead of
#   re-running from scratch.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from cmd/breakpoint/*.go
#                       cobra-based subcommand declarations,
#                       extracted via `gh api repos/namespacelabs
#                       /breakpoint/contents/cmd/breakpoint/...`)
#
#   breakpoint <SUBCOMMAND> [flags...]
#
#   Subcommands:
#     start                          Starts breakpoint in the
#                                    background (begins watching
#                                    the trigger and stands ready
#                                    to pause + notify)
#       --config <PATH>                Path to the configuration
#                                      file
#
#     wait                           Blocks for the duration of
#                                    the breakpoint (foreground
#                                    invocation; CI step that
#                                    holds the job until the hold
#                                    expires)
#       --config <PATH>                Path to the configuration
#                                      file
#
#     status                         Get the current status of
#                                    breakpoint (running / paused
#                                    / SSH endpoint exposed)
#
#     hold                           Holds until a breakpoint is
#                                    finished or for a certain
#                                    amount of time
#       --for <DURATION>               How much to extend the
#                                      breakpoint by
#                                      [default: 30m]
#       --duration <DURATION>          Alias of --for
#       --while-connected              Keep holding while there
#                                      are active connections,
#                                      even after duration has
#                                      passed
#       --stop                         Stop the breakpoint server
#                                      after holding
#
#     extend                         Extend the breakpoint
#                                    duration
#       --for <DURATION>               How much to extend the
#                                      breakpoint by
#                                      [default: 30m]
#       --duration <DURATION>          Alias of --for
#
#     resume                         Resume the workflow
#                                    execution (release the pause
#                                    + tear down the SSH endpoint)
#
#     attach                         Attach to a running
#                                    breakpoint (the SSH-jack-in
#                                    helper that the Slack
#                                    notification links to)
#       --endpoint <ADDR>              The address of the server
#       --target <ADDR>                Where to connect to
#
#   Standard cobra auto-flags:
#     -h, --help                     Show help (also per
#                                    subcommand)
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `github.com/slack-go/slack v0.12.2`
#   declared in go.mod — `slack-go/slack` is THE canonical Go
#   Slack SDK, originally `nlopes/slack` and now maintained by
#   the slack-go org (slack-go/slack, 4,600+ stars; the
#   predominant typed Slack client in the Go ecosystem, used by
#   every major Go project that talks to Slack — Argo Rollouts,
#   CockroachDB ops, Atlantis, Gort, Cerbos reimage, Infracost,
#   Inspektor, ReSim, namespacelabs/breakpoint, dozens of
#   internal corporate bots, and most cobra-based CLIs that
#   surface CI notifications).  slack-go/slack exposes the typed
#   `slack.Client` constructor with `slack.New(token,
#   slack.OptionDebug(...), slack.OptionHTTPClient(...))`, the
#   typed `slack.PostMessageParameters` request builder + the
#   `slack.PostMessage(channelID, slack.MsgOptionText(...),
#   slack.MsgOptionAttachments(...), slack.MsgOptionBlocks(...),
#   slack.MsgOptionThreadTs(...))` chain, every
#   `slack.UpdateMessage` / `slack.DeleteMessage` /
#   `slack.GetConversationsForUser` /
#   `slack.GetConversationInfo` / `slack.GetUserInfo` /
#   `slack.GetUsersInfo` / `slack.LookupUserByEmail` /
#   `slack.UploadFileV2` / `slack.OpenView` / `slack.UpdateView`
#   / `slack.PushView` request + response model, the typed Block
#   Kit primitives (`slack.HeaderBlock`, `slack.SectionBlock`,
#   `slack.DividerBlock`, `slack.ActionBlock`, `slack.ContextBlock`,
#   `slack.ImageBlock`, `slack.FileBlock`, `slack.VideoBlock`,
#   `slack.RichTextBlock`, `slack.MarkdownTextObject`,
#   `slack.PlainTextObject`, every `BlockElement` variant —
#   `slack.ButtonBlockElement`, `slack.SelectBlockElement`,
#   `slack.MultiSelectBlockElement`, `slack.OverflowBlockElement`,
#   `slack.DatePickerBlockElement`, `slack.PlainTextInputBlock
#   Element`, etc.), the `slack.MsgOption*` modifier set, the
#   typed Events API parser (`slackevents.ParseEvent`,
#   `slackevents.EventsAPIEvent`, every
#   `slackevents.AppMentionEvent` / `MessageEvent` /
#   `ReactionAddedEvent` / `FileCreatedEvent` / etc. variant),
#   the Socket-Mode client (`socketmode.New`,
#   `socketmode.Client.Run`), interactive callbacks
#   (`slack.InteractionCallback`), slash-command callbacks
#   (`slack.SlashCommand`), modal-view submissions, and the
#   request-verifier (`slack.NewSecretsVerifier(headers,
#   signingSecret)`) for inbound webhook validation.
#   breakpoint's `pkg/notifier/slack/...` uses
#   `slack.New(botToken)` to construct a typed Slack client per
#   started breakpoint, builds a `slack.HeaderBlock` +
#   `slack.SectionBlock` payload announcing "CI workflow paused
#   — endpoint <ssh://...>" with the SSH endpoint as a clickable
#   link, and posts it to the configured channel via
#   `client.PostMessage(channelID, slack.MsgOptionBlocks(...))`.
